name: Ave
description: A material design IRC client written in HTML, CSS, and JavaScript.

releases.name: v0.4 beta 2
releases.body:
The second beta for v0.4. This release should be substantially more stable (and more usable) than the previous beta.

OS Install options:
- Linux provides both a .tar.gz standalone binary package, and a .deb installer for each linux architecture (excluding armv7l, which does not have a .deb).
- Windows provides a standalone binary .exe (.msi installer on its way), contained in a .zip file.
- Mac provides a generically-signed .app folder/file. (Not massively sure how Mac apps work; you should probably be comfortable with mac though.) This is contained in a .tar.gz file.

releases.name: 0.4.0 beta 1
releases.body:
- [x] Refactored client back-end for better maintenance (PARTIAL for beta 1)
- [x] Added websocket server for API (MOST for beta 1)
- [ ] Plugin system implemented
- Added "cancel" button to server editor page, discarding changes.

The primary focus of this release is the introduction of the new server dashboard, allowing a clean, Material Design method to easily, and quickly, jump straight in to your favourite servers.
- Added new server dashboard styled off Material Design.
- Bug fixes.

New user support is finally complete! Naturally, this is probably gonna be improved and tweaked in future, but all projects do that.

0.2 improves aspects that confuse new users, adding a small jargon buster and improving the terminology used in PARTing from channels to better describe the function to new users.
- Added support for connecting to password-protected servers.
- Support responding to CTCP VERSION requests
- Fixed issue with searching users undoing the lag fix from 0.1.2.
- Added "jargon buster" to welcome screen.
- Changed "Leave IRC Chat" text to be more descriptive
- Markdown support

releases.name: [Beta] 0.1.2
releases.body:
(Forgot to release 0.1.1 a few days ago; oops)

Cleaned up stuff since 0.1, and the client is a fair bit more usable (and no longer lags like hell on `##javascript` and `#node.js` on Freenode).
- Added warning to reconnect function
- Added unread message tooltip
- Fixed nickname case-sensitivity
- Fixed issue in which large channels lagged the client whilst active

releases.name: Client Proper Created
releases.body: The basics for the Ave IRC Client are implemented, making conversing using IRC entirely plausible at the moment.
